If I have this swagger spec
'''
{
    "swagger": "2.0",
    "info": {
        "title": " ",
        "version": "0.0.0"
    },
    "paths": {
        "/foo": {
            "get": {
                "responses": {
                    "200": {
                        "description": " ",
                        "schema": {
                            "$ref": "foo.json#/common"
                        }
                    }
                }
            }
        },
        "/bar": {
            "get": {
                "responses": {
                    "200": {
                        "description": " ",
                        "schema": {
                            "$ref": "bar.json#/common"
                        }
                    }
                }
            }
        }
    }
}
'''
There "common" references in two different files. Lets assume foo.json looks like this
'''
{
    "common": {
        "$ref": "#definitions/common"
    },
    "definitions": {
        "common": {
            "type": "integer"
        }
    }
}
'''
And bar.json looks like this:
'''
{
    "common": {
        "$ref": "#definitions/common"
    },
    "definitions": {
        "common": {
            "type": "string"
        }
    }
}
'''
When I call api.resolve_refs on my spec, my defs dict will look something like this:
'''
{
        ":....bar.json|..common": {
            "$ref": "#/definitions/:....bar.json|definitions..common"
        },
        ":....foo.json|..common": {
            "$ref": "#/definitions/:....foo.json|definitions..common"
        },
        ":....|definitions..common": {
            "type": "integer"
        }
    }
'''
As you can see, the definition in bar.json for common being a string has been overwritten.

