I was reading [this presentation](http://files.opensuse.org/opensuse/en/b/b9/Fosdem2008-solver.pdf) about zypper, the OpenSuse package mangaer, which also uses a SAT solver. It mentions that when packages are unsatisfiable, to report to the user what rules are the cause.

This is a good idea. Conda currently reports what packages can be removed to make the rest satisfiable, but you have to deduce what the issue is from that. And [sometimes](https://github.com/conda/conda/issues/567) it's not very helpful. Instead of reporting "removing package X would make things work", we should report, "the rule(s) X is the issue here", where it could be something like "X depends on Y and Y conflicts with Z" (the most common occurrence of unsatisfiable packages is a package not being built for a particular version of Python) or "X and Y cannot be installed together".

